    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Wilkes Barre</placeName>
                <date>December 23<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5613 <add>1852</add></date>
            </p>
            <p><addressee>Reverend Isaac Leeser</addressee>, <placeName>Pa.</placeName></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir, Having the pleasure of being already introduced<lb/> to
                you—occasionally, when for two years ago I presented you<lb/> my little work,
                styled: Polyglott Porkesbook<add>?</add> in 6 different languages—<lb/> you will
                pardon me for the liberty I take now by forwarding to you<lb/> some sheets of a new
                work, which since my reentering upon<lb/> the duty of ministry here, in
                    <placeName>Wilkes Barre</placeName>, has taken up my hours<lb/> of leisure. It
                is this a translation of <persName>D. Ottensoser's</persName><lb/> work, called<lb/>
                <add>געשיכטע דער יהודים [אונד איהרער ליטעראטור</add><lb/> into the English. The
                merit of this work is mainly:</p>
            <list type="ordered">
                <item n="1">its being based upon the best Historians of ours,<lb/> as the authors of
                    the books <add>פאן איהרער ריקקעהר אויז דער באבילאנישען געפאנגענשאפט</add>,
                        <persName>Josephus</persName>, u.s.f.</item>
                <item n="2">its adopting the pious principle, that the traditions of<lb/> our
                        <sic>forfathers</sic> must be for us a law; they must not<lb/> depart from
                    our mouth and from the mouth of our children<lb/> from henceforth and for
                    evermore.</item>
                <item n="3">The author never neglects to point out in especial notes<lb/> the
                        <sic>souces</sic>, out of which his statements are
                    <sic>depickted</sic>;</item>
                <item n="4">its completeness. The author sought never to overlook<lb/> any important
                    fact, and to relate in a noble and powerful</item>
            </list>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>style without to weary the curiosity of the reader with<lb/> useless triflings, and
                5. its cheapness.—$2.00 for the whole—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am of opinion, that a History of our people, managed<lb/> under
                such aspects and written in the Vernacular cannot<lb/> but prove great utility both
                to families and schools.<lb/> But even to scholars of profession a work of that
                kind<lb/> must open a wide field for investigations inasmuch as<lb/> it differs from
                other Historians and as it offers an acquaintance<lb/> with a large part of jewish
                Literature.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As far as my small ability goes I did all I could<lb/> to render the
                author's ideas faithfully and to give a correct<lb/> transcript of the original,
                though many notes and explanations<lb/> are anexed<add>?</add> which I thought
                proper to insert.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now from the above <sic>motivs</sic>, and—if you like—to<lb/>
                overread the <sic>inclosed</sic> few sheets you, a most competent<lb/> judge easily
                can decide, whether a work of that kind<lb/> will meet the taste and favor of the
                public or not.<lb/> Have no regard whatever for myself if you find fault<lb/> with
                that what now is subject to your judgment, and<lb/> favor me with your opinion about
                it. IN case,<lb/> that the proof should meet your <sic>aprobation</sic> and you were
                of<lb/> opinion, that the public likewise may welcome it, then I<lb/> again will
                enter upon the purifying and conclusion of the<lb/> work. Meanwhile you would oblige
                me very much if you<lb/> were pleased to insert the <sic>anexed</sic>
                <hi rend="underline">Call</hi> in the next<lb/> numbers of your high esteemed „<hi
                    rend="underline">Occident</hi>” accompanied by</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>a few words of recommendation and to induce your agents<lb/> to receive
                subscriptions. Of course, in order that the public<lb/> may be able to form an idea
                of that what there may to be<lb/> expected it becomes necessary to have a specimen
                before<lb/> their eyes. One or two chapters of the work inserted in your<lb/>
                esteemed Periodical would answer the purpose—if you<lb/> like to do so.—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Please and send me up the following months of the<lb/> „Occident” of
                this year, [<sic>inclosed</sic> you will receive the amount for],<lb/> and so I am
                in possession of the <hi rend="underline">ten volumes</hi> of the above<lb/>
                Periodical, but most of them being not complete, you will show me<lb/> another great
                favor by forwarding to me those numbers, which<lb/> I am lacking, to a moderate
                price. Viz:</p>
            <p>of Vol. I, year <date>1843</date>, the numbers....<hi rend="underline"
                >2.3.4.6</hi></p>
            <p>“ Vol. II, year <date>1844</date> “ “ ......10.11.12.</p>
            <p>“ Vol. IV, year <date>1846</date>. “ “ .... 1.2.3.4.5.6.8.</p>
            <p>“ Vol. V year <date>1847</date>, “ “ 6, 9, 12.</p>
            <p>“ Vol. VI year <date>1848</date> “ “ 1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 11, 12.</p>
            <p>“ Vol. VII yr. <date>1849</date> “ “ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 9, 10, 12.</p>
            <p>The following volumes till presently are complete.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In expectation a kind reply, I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Reverend Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">your most obedt. Servant</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Strause</persName>
            </p>
